# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: airbreathing-jet-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/addison-wesley-publishing-company] The Addison–Wesley Professional Imprint produces content including books, eBooks, and video for the professional IT worker including developers, programmers, managers, system administrators.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/addison-wesley-publishing-company] Classic titles include *The Art of Computer Programming*, *The C++ Programming Language*, *The Mythical Man-Month*, and *Design Patterns*.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/addison-wesley-publishing-company] Lew Addison Cummings and Melbourne Wesley Cummings founded Addison–Wesley in 1942, with the first book published by Addison–Wesley being Massachusetts Institute of Technology professor Francis Weston Sears' *Mechanics*.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/addison-wesley-publishing-company] Its first computer book was *Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer*, by Wilkes, Wheeler, and Gill.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/addison-wesley-publishing-company] Benjamin Company, and merged it with the Cummings division of the company to form Benjamin Cummings.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/addison-wesley-publishing-company] It was purchased by the global publishing and education company Pearson PLC in 1988 and became part of Addison Wesley Longman in 1994.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/addison-wesley-publishing-company] The trade publishing division of Addison–Wesley was sold to Perseus Books Group in 1997, leaving Addison–Wesley as solely an educational publisher.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/addison-wesley-publishing-company] Pearson acquired the educational division of Simon & Schuster in 1998, and merged it with Addison Wesley Longman to form Pearson Education and subsequently rebranded to Pearson in 2011.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/addison-wesley-publishing-company] Pearson moved the former Addison Wesley Longman offices from Reading, Massachusetts, to Boston in 2004.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/addison-wesley-publishing-company] Its current executives hail from the original Addison–Wesley with a storied history of their own.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] "For high speed aircraft and missiles aerodynamic heating is the conversion of kinetic energy into heat energy as a result of their relative motion in stationary air and the subsequent transfer through the skin into the structure and interior of the vehicle.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] Some heat is produced by fluid compression at and near stagnation points such as the vehicle nose and wing leading edges.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] Additional heat is generated from air friction along the skin inside the boundary layer".
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] These two regions of skin heating are shown by van Driest.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] Boundary layer heating of the skin may be known as kinetic heating.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] The effects of aerodynamic heating on the temperature of the skin, and subsequent heat transfer into the structure, the cabin, the equipment bays and the electrical, hydraulic and fuel systems, have to be incorporated in the design of supersonic and hypersonic aircraft and missiles.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] One of the main concerns caused by aerodynamic heating arises in the design of the wing.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] For subsonic speeds, two main goals of wing design are minimizing weight and maximizing strength.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] Aerodynamic heating, which occurs at supersonic and hypersonic speeds, adds an additional consideration in wing structure analysis.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] An idealized wing structure is made up of spars, stringers, and skin segments.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] In a wing that normally experiences subsonic speeds, there must be a sufficient number of stringers to withstand the axial and bending stresses induced by the lift force acting on the wing.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] In addition, the distance between the stringers must be small enough that the skin panels do not buckle, and the panels must be thick enough to withstand the shear stress and shear flow present in the panels due to the lifting force on the wing.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] However, the weight of the wing must be made as small as possible, so the choice of material for the stringers and the skin is an important factor.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] At supersonic speeds, aerodynamic heating adds another element to this structural analysis.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] At normal speeds, spars and stringers experience a load which is a function of the lift force, first and second moments of inertia, and length of the spar.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] When there are more spars and stringers, the load in each member is reduced, and the area of the stringer can be reduced to meet critical stress requirements.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] However, the increase in temperature caused by energy flowing from the air (heated by skin friction at these high speeds) adds another load factor, called a thermal load, to the spars.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] This thermal load increases the force felt by the stringers, and thus the area of the stringers must be increased in order for the critical stress requirement to be met.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] Another issue that aerodynamic heating causes for aircraft design is the effect of high temperatures on common material properties.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] Common materials used in aircraft wing design, such as aluminum and steel, experience a decrease in strength as temperatures get extremely high.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] The Young's Modulus of the material, defined as the ratio between stress and strain experienced by the material, decreases as the temperature increases.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] Young's Modulus is critical in the selection of materials for wing, as a higher value lets the material resist the yield and shear stress caused by the lift and thermal loads.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] This is because Young's Modulus is an important factor in the equations for calculating the critical buckling load for axial members and the critical buckling shear stress for skin panels.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] If the Young's Modulus of the material decreases at high temperatures caused by aerodynamic heating, then the wing design will call for larger spars and thicker skin segments in order to account for this decrease in strength as the aircraft goes supersonic.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] There are some materials that retain their strength at the high temperatures that aerodynamic heating induces.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] For example, Inconel X-750 was used on parts of the airframe of the X-15, a North American aircraft that flew at hypersonic speeds in 1958.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] Titanium is another high-strength material, even at high temperatures, and is often used for wing frames of supersonic aircraft.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] The SR-71 used titanium skin panels painted black to reduce the temperature and corrugated to accommodate expansion.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] Another important design concept for early supersonic aircraft wings was using a small thickness-to-chord ratio, so that the speed of the flow over the airfoil does not increase too much from the free stream speed.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] As the flow is already supersonic, increasing the speed even more would not be beneficial for the wing structure.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] Reducing the thickness of the wing brings the top and bottom stringers closer together, reducing the total moment of inertia of the structure.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] This increases axial load in the stringers, and thus the area, and weight, of the stringers must be increased.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] Some designs for hypersonic missiles have used liquid cooling of the leading edges (usually the fuel en route to the engine).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] The Sprint missile's heat shield needed several design iterations for Mach 10 temperatures.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] Heating caused by the very high reentry speeds (greater than Mach 20) is sufficient to destroy the vehicle unless special techniques are used.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] The early space capsules such as used on Mercury, Gemini, and Apollo were given blunt shapes to produce a stand-off bow shock, allowing most of the heat to dissipate into the surrounding air.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] Additionally, these vehicles had ablative material that sublimates into a gas at high temperature.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] The act of sublimation absorbs the thermal energy from the aerodynamic heating and erodes the material rather than heating the capsule.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] The surface of the heat shield for the Mercury spacecraft had a coating of aluminium with glassfiber in many layers.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] As the temperature rose to 1,100 °C (1,400 K) the layers would evaporate and take the heat with it.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] The spacecraft would become hot but not harmfully so.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] The Space Shuttle used insulating tiles on its lower surface to absorb and radiate heat while preventing conduction to the aluminium airframe.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/aerodynamic-heating] Damage to the heat shield during liftoff of Space Shuttle *Columbia* contributed to its destruction upon reentry.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] An **afterburner** (or **reheat** in British English) is an additional combustion component used on some jet engines, mostly those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Its purpose is to increase thrust, usually for supersonic flight, takeoff, and combat.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The afterburning process injects additional fuel into a combustor ("burner") in the jet pipe behind (i.e., "after") the turbine, "reheating" the exhaust gas.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Afterburning significantly increases thrust and is used as an alternative to a larger, heavier engine.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] However, it increases fuel consumption and decreases fuel efficiency, which limits its use to short periods.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] This aircraft application of "reheat" contrasts with the meaning and implementation of "reheat" applicable to gas turbines driving electrical generators and which reduces fuel consumption.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning and *dry* when not.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power,* while an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power*.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The first jet engine with after-burner was the E variant of the Jumo 004.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Jet-engine thrust is an application of Newton's reaction principle, in which the engine generates thrust because it increases the momentum of the air passing through it.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Thrust depends on two things: the velocity of the exhaust gas and the mass of the gas exiting the nozzle.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] A jet engine can produce more thrust by either accelerating the gas to a higher velocity or ejecting a greater mass of gas from the engine.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Designing a basic turbojet engine around the second principle produces the turbofan engine, which creates slower gas, but more of it.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Turbofans are highly fuel efficient and can deliver high thrust for long periods of time, but the design tradeoff is a large size relative to the power output.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Generating increased power with a more compact engine for short periods can be achieved using an afterburner.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The afterburner increases thrust primarily by accelerating the exhaust gas to a higher velocity.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The following values and parameters are for an early jet engine, the Pratt & Whitney J57, stationary on the runway, and illustrate the high values of afterburner fuel flow, gas temperature and thrust compared to those for the engine operating within the temperature limitations for its turbine.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The highest temperature in the engine (about 3,700 °F (2,040 °C) occurs in the combustion chamber, where fuel is burned (at an approximate rate of 8,520 lb/h (3,860 kg/h)) in a relatively small proportion of the air entering the engine.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The combustion products have to be diluted with air from the compressor to bring the gas temperature down to a specific value, known as the Turbine Entry Temperature (TET) (1,570 °F (850 °C)), which gives the turbine an acceptable life.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Having to reduce the temperature of the combustion products by a large amount is one of the primary limitations on how much thrust can be generated (10,200 lbf (45,000 N)).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The gas temperature decreases as it passes through the turbine (to 1,013 °F (545 °C)).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The afterburner combustor reheats the gas, but to a much higher temperature (2,540 °F (1,390 °C)) than the TET (1,570 °F (850 °C)).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] As a result of the temperature rise in the afterburner combustor, the gas is accelerated, firstly by the heat addition, known as Rayleigh flow, then by the nozzle to a higher exit velocity than that which occurs without the afterburner.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The mass flow is also slightly increased by the addition of the afterburner fuel.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The thrust with afterburning is 16,000 lbf (71,000 N).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The visible exhaust may show *shock diamonds*, which are caused by shock waves formed due to slight differences between ambient pressure and the exhaust pressure.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] This interaction causes oscillations in the exhaust jet diameter over a short distance and causes visible banding where pressure and temperature are highest.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Thrust may be increased by burning fuel in a turbofan's cold bypass air, instead of the mixed cold and hot flows as in most afterburning turbofans.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] An early augmented turbofan, the Pratt & Whitney TF30, used separate burning zones for the bypass and core flows with three of seven concentric spray rings in the bypass flow.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] In comparison, the afterburning Rolls-Royce Spey used a twenty chute mixer before the fuel manifolds.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Plenum chamber burning (PCB) was partially developed for the vectored thrust Bristol Siddeley BS100 engine for the Hawker Siddeley P.1154 until the program was cancelled in 1965.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The cold bypass and hot core flows were split between two pairs of nozzles, front and rear, in the same manner as the Rolls-Royce Pegasus, and fuel was burned in the fan air before it left the front nozzles.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] It would have given greater thrust for take-off and supersonic performance in an aircraft similar to, but bigger than, the Hawker Siddeley Harrier.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Duct heating was used by Pratt & Whitney for their JTF17 turbofan proposal for the U.S.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Supersonic Transport Program in 1964 and a demonstrator engine was run.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The duct heater used an annular combustor and would be used for takeoff, climb and cruise at Mach 2.7 with different amounts of augmentation depending on aircraft weight.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] A jet engine afterburner is an extended exhaust section containing extra fuel injectors.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Since the jet engine upstream (i.e., before the turbine) will use little of the oxygen it ingests, additional fuel can be burned after the gas flow has left the turbines.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] When the afterburner is turned on, fuel is injected and igniters are fired.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The resulting combustion process increases the afterburner exit (nozzle entry) temperature, resulting in a significant increase in engine thrust.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The resulting increase in afterburner exit volume flow is accommodated by increasing the throat area of the exit nozzle.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Otherwise, if pressure is not released, the gas can flow upstream and re-ignite, possibly causing a compressor stall (or fan surge in a turbofan application).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Solar afterburners used on the F7U Cutlass, F-94 Starfire and F-89 Scorpion, had 2-position eyelid nozzles.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Modern designs incorporate not only variable-geometry (VG) nozzles but multiple stages of augmentation via separate spray bars.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] To a first order, the gross thrust ratio (afterburning/dry) is directly proportional to the root of the stagnation temperature ratio across the afterburner (i.e. exit/entry).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Due to their high fuel consumption, afterburners are only used for short-duration, high-thrust requirements.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] These include heavy-weight or short-runway take-offs, assisting catapult launches from aircraft carriers, and during air combat.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] A notable exception is the Pratt & Whitney J58 engine used in the SR-71 Blackbird which used its afterburner for prolonged periods and was refueled in-flight as part of every reconnaissance mission.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] An afterburner has a limited life to match its intermittent use.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The J58 was an exception with a continuous rating.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] This was achieved with thermal barrier coatings on the liner and flame holders and by cooling the liner and nozzle with compressor bleed air instead of turbine exhaust gas.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] In heat engines such as jet engines, efficiency is highest when combustion occurs at the highest pressure and temperature possible, and expanded down to ambient pressure (see Carnot cycle).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Since the exhaust gas already has a reduced oxygen content, owing to previous combustion, and since the fuel is not burning in a highly compressed air column, the afterburner is generally inefficient in comparison to the main combustion process.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Afterburner efficiency also declines significantly if, as is usually the case, the inlet and tailpipe pressure decreases with increasing altitude.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] This limitation applies only to turbojets.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] In a military turbofan combat engine, the bypass air is added into the exhaust, thereby increasing the core and afterburner efficiency.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] In turbojets the gain is limited to 50%, whereas in a turbofan it depends on the bypass ratio and can be as much as 70%.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] However, as a counterexample, the SR-71 had reasonable efficiency at high altitude in afterburning ("wet") mode owing to its high speed (Mach 3.2) and correspondingly high pressure due to ram intake.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Afterburning has a significant influence upon engine cycle choice.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Lowering the fan pressure ratio decreases specific thrust (both dry and wet afterburning), but results in a lower temperature entering the afterburner.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Since the afterburning exit temperature is effectively fixed, the temperature rise across the unit increases, raising the afterburner fuel flow.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The total fuel flow tends to increase faster than the net thrust, resulting in a higher specific fuel consumption (SFC).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] However, the corresponding dry power SFC improves (i.e. lower specific thrust).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The high temperature ratio across the afterburner results in a good thrust boost.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] If the aircraft burns a large percentage of its fuel with the afterburner alight, it pays to select an engine cycle with a high specific thrust (i.e. high fan pressure ratio/low bypass ratio).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The resulting engine is relatively fuel efficient with afterburning (i.e.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Combat/Take-off), but thirsty in dry power.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] If, however, the afterburner is to be hardly used, a low specific thrust (low fan pressure ratio/high bypass ratio) cycle will be favored.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Such an engine has a good dry SFC, but a poor afterburning SFC at Combat/Take-off.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Often the engine designer is faced with a compromise between these two extremes.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The Caproni Campini C.C.2 motorjet, designed by the Italian engineer Secondo Campini, was the first aircraft to incorporate an afterburner.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The first flight of a C.C.2, with its afterburners operating, took place on 11 April 1941.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Early British afterburner ("reheat") work included flight tests on a Rolls-Royce W2/B23 in a Gloster Meteor I in late 1944 and ground tests on a Power Jets W2/700 engine in mid-1945.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] This engine was destined for the Miles M.52 supersonic aircraft project.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Early American research on the concept was done by NACA, in Cleveland, Ohio, leading to the publication of the paper "Theoretical Investigation of Thrust Augmentation of Turbojet Engines by Tail-pipe Burning" in January 1947.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] American work on afterburners in 1948 resulted in installations on early straight-wing jets such as the Pirate, Starfire and Scorpion.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The new Pratt & Whitney J48 turbojet, at 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust with afterburners, would power the Grumman swept-wing fighter F9F-6, which was about to go into production.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Other new Navy fighters with afterburners included the Chance Vought F7U-3 Cutlass, powered by two 6,000 lbf (27 kN) thrust Westinghouse J46 engines.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] In the 1950s, several large afterburning engines were developed, such as the Orenda Iroquois and the British de Havilland Gyron and Rolls-Royce Avon RB.146 variants.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The Avon and its variants powered the English Electric Lightning, the first supersonic aircraft in RAF service.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The Bristol-Siddeley/Rolls-Royce Olympus was fitted with afterburners for use with the BAC TSR-2.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] This system was designed and developed jointly by Bristol-Siddeley and Solar of San Diego.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The afterburner system for the Concorde was developed by Snecma.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Afterburners are generally used only in military aircraft, and are considered standard equipment on fighter aircraft.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] The handful of civilian planes that have used them include some NASA research aircraft, the Tupolev Tu-144, Concorde and the White Knight of Scaled Composites.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Concorde flew long distances at supersonic speeds.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Sustained high speeds would be impossible with the high fuel consumption of afterburner, and the plane used afterburners at takeoff and to minimize time spent in the high-drag transonic flight regime.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Supersonic flight without afterburners is referred to as supercruise.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] A turbojet engine equipped with an afterburner is called an "afterburning turbojet", whereas a turbofan engine similarly equipped is sometimes called an "augmented turbofan".
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] A "dump-and-burn" is an airshow display feature where fuel is jettisoned, then intentionally ignited using the afterburner.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] A spectacular flame combined with high speed makes this a popular display for airshows, or as a finale to fireworks.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Fuel dumping is used primarily to reduce the weight of an aircraft to avoid a heavy, high-speed landing.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/afterburner-engine] Other than for safety or emergency reasons, fuel dumping does not have a practical use.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Aviation security is focused on protecting air travelers, aircraft and infrastructure from intentional harm or disruption, rather than unintentional mishaps.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Aviation is safer today than it has ever been.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Modern commercial aviation boasts an accident rate of approximately 1 fatal accident per 16 million flights, far lower than historic numbers.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] On December 14, 1903, the Wright Brothers conducted a test flight of their powered airplane from the slope of Big Kill Devil Hill in North Carolina.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Upon takeoff, the airplane lifted about 15 feet off the ground, stalled, and crashed into the sand.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Only three days later, on December 17, 1903, Wilbur's brother, Orville Wright flew the airplane for the world's first powered, sustained, and controlled heavier-than-air flight in history.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Although the failed test flight on December 14 would be mostly forgotten in aviation, it remains one of the earliest recorded aviation accidents in history.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In the early years of air travel, accidents were exceedingly common.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In 1928 and 1929, the overall accident rate was about 1 in every million miles (1.6 million kilometers) flown.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In today's industry, that accident rate would translate to about 7,000 fatal accidents each year.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] For the ten-year period 2002 to 2011, 0.6 fatal accidents happened per one million flights globally, 0.4 per million hours flown, 22.0 fatalities per one million flights or 12.7 per million hours flown.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] From 310 million passengers in 1970, air transport had grown to 3,696 million in 2016, led by 823 million in the United States, then 488 million in China.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In 2016, 19 fatal accidents involved civil airliners with more than 14 passengers.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] These accidents resulted in 325 fatalities, the second safest year ever after 2015 with 16 accidents and 2013 with 265 fatalities.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] For planes heavier than 5.7 metric tones, there were 34.9 million departures and 75 accidents worldwide with 7 of these fatal for 182 fatalities, the lowest since 2013 : 5.21 fatalities per million departures.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In 2017, there were 10 fatal airliner accidents, resulting in 44 occupant fatalities and 35 persons on the ground: the safest year ever for commercial aviation, both by the number of fatal accidents as well as in fatalities.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] By 2019, fatal accidents per million flights decreased 12 fold since 1970, from 6.35 to 0.51, and fatalities per trillion revenue passenger kilometre (RPK) decreased 81 fold from 3,218 to 40.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Runway safety represents 36% of accidents, ground safety 18% and loss of control in-flight 16%.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Loss of control inflight represents 35% of the fatal accidents, Controlled flight into terrain 21%, runway excursions 17%, system or component failure: 6%, Touchdown off the runway: 5%, Abnormal Runway Contact: 4% and fire: 2%.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Safety has improved from better aircraft design process, engineering and maintenance, the evolution of navigation aids, and safety protocols and procedures.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] There are three main ways in which the risk of fatality in a certain mode of travel can be measured: (1) deaths per billion typical *journeys* taken, (2) deaths per billion *hours* traveled, and (3) deaths per billion *kilometers* traveled.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The following table displays these statistics for the United Kingdom (1990–2000), and has been appended.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The first two statistics are computed for typical travels by their respective forms of transport, so they cannot be used directly to compare risks related to different forms of transport in a particular travel "from A to B".
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] For example, these statistics suggest that a typical flight from Los Angeles to New York would carry a larger risk factor than a typical car travel from home to office.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] However, car travel from Los Angeles to New York would not be typical; that journey would be as long as *several dozen* typical car travels, and thus the associated risk would be larger as well.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Because the journey would take a much longer time, the overall risk associated with making this journey by car would be higher than making the same journey by air, even if each individual hour of car travel is less risky than each hour of flight.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] For risks associated with long-range intercity travel, the most suitable statistic is the third one: deaths per billion kilometers.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Still, this statistic can lose credence in situations where the availability of an air option makes an otherwise inconvenient journey possible.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Aviation industry insurers base their calculations on the *deaths per journey* statistic while the aviation industry itself generally uses the *deaths per kilometre* statistic in press releases.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Since 1997, the number of fatal air accidents has been no more than 1 for every 2,000,000,000 person-miles flown, and thus is one of the safest modes of transportation when measured by distance traveled.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Because the above figures are focused on providing a perspective to the realm of everyday transportation, air travel is taken to include only standard civil passenger aviation, as offered commercially to the general public.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Military and special-purpose aircraft are excluded.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Between 1990 and 2015, there were 1874 commuter and air taxi accidents in the U.S. of which 454 (24%) were fatal, resulting in 1,296 deaths, including 674 accidents (36%) and 279 fatalities (22%) in Alaska alone.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The number of deaths per passenger-mile on commercial airlines in the United States between 2000 and 2010 was about 0.2 deaths per 10 billion passenger-miles.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] For driving, the rate was 150 per 10 billion vehicle-miles for 2000: 750 times higher per mile than for flying in a commercial airplane.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] There were no fatalities on large scheduled commercial airlines in the United States for over nine years, between the Colgan Air Flight 3407 crash in February 2009, and a catastrophic engine failure on Southwest Airlines Flight 1380 in April 2018.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Another aspect of safety is protection from intentional harm or property damage, also known as *security*.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The terrorist attacks of 2001 are not counted as accidents.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] However, even if they were counted as accidents they would have added about 1 death per billion person-miles.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Two months later, American Airlines Flight 587 crashed in New York City, killing 265 people, including 5 on the ground, causing 2001 to show a very high fatality rate.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Even so, the rate that year including the attacks (estimated here to be about 4 deaths per billion person-miles), is safe compared to some other forms of transport when measured by distance traveled.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The first aircraft electrical or electronic device avionics system was Lawrence Sperry's autopilot, demonstrated in June 1914.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The Transcontinental Airway System chain of beacons was built by the Commerce Department in 1923 to guide airmail flights.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Gyrocopters were developed by Juan de la Cierva to avoid stall and spin accidents, and for that invented cyclic and collective controls used by helicopters.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The first flight of a gyrocopter was on June 9th, 1923.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] A network of aerial lighthouses was established in the United Kingdom and Europe during the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Use of the lighthouses has declined with the advent of radio navigation aids such as non-directional beacon (NDB), VHF omnidirectional range (VOR), and distance measuring equipment (DME).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The last operational aerial lighthouse in the United Kingdom is on top of the cupola over the RAF College main hall at RAF Cranwell.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] One of the first aids for air navigation to be introduced in the United States in the late 1920s was airfield lighting, to assist pilots in making landings in poor weather or after dark.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The Precision Approach Path Indicator (PAPI) was developed from this in the 1930s, indicating to the pilot the angle of descent to the airfield.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] This later became adopted internationally through the standards of the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Jimmy Doolittle developed instrument rating and made his first 'blind' flight in September 1929.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The March 1931 wooden wing failure of a Transcontinental & Western Air Fokker F-10 carrying Knute Rockne, coach of the University of Notre Dame's football team, showed cause for all-metal airframes and led to a more formal accident investigation system.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] On 4 September 1933, a Douglas DC-1 test flight was conducted with one of the two engines shut down during the takeoff run, climbed to 8,000 feet (2,438 metres), and completed its flight, proving twin aircraft engine safety.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] ILS was first used by a scheduled flight to make a landing in a snowstorm at Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, in 1938, and a form of ILS was adopted by the ICAO for international use in 1949.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Hard runways were built worldwide for World War II to avoid waves and floating hazards plaguing seaplanes.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Developed by the U.S. and introduced during World War II, LORAN replaced the sailors' less reliable compass and celestial navigation over water and survived until it was replaced by the Global Positioning System.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Following the development of radar in World War II, it was deployed as a landing aid for civil aviation in the form of ground-controlled approach (GCA) systems then as the airport surveillance radar as an aid to air traffic control in the 1950s.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] A number of ground-based weather radar systems can detect areas of precipitation such as thunderstorms, which are associated with severe turbulence.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] A modern Honeywell Intuvue weather system visualizes weather patterns up to 300 miles (480 km) away.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] From 1988, Fly-By-Wire (in the A220, A320 family, A330/A340, A350, A380, B777, B787 and Embraer E-Jets) enabled flight envelope protection to reduce LOC in flight accidents.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The fatal accident rate fell from 3.0 per million flights for the first generation to 0.9 for the next, 0.3 for the third and 0.1 for the last.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] However, certain aircraft have higher than average hull loss rates, such as the F28, MD-11, Concorde, and A310 due to various circumstances and/or design decisions.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] According to Boeing's Statistical Summary of Commercial Jet Airplane Accidents 1959–2024, the F28 has a hull loss rate of 4.62 per million flights.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] This is significantly higher than similar aircraft of its era, such as the 737-100/200 and DC-9, which have loss rates of 1.78 and 1.45 respectively.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Similarly, the A310 and MD-11 have unusually high hull loss rates, with the A310 having the highest fatal hull loss rate and the MD-11 having the highest overall rate of all widebody commercial airliners.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In the 1959–2003 edition, the Concorde is listed as having a hull loss rate of 11.36 per million flights as a result of its low number of flights.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Consequently, its loss rate is higher than both the DC-8 and 707 (which have rates of 9.15 and 5.82 in that edition).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Aircraft with high loss rates often have fundamental design flaws.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The F28 has a known sensitivity to icing, which has led to numerous accidents including Air Ontario Flight 1363 and USAir Flight 405.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Similarly, the MD-11 incorporated a relaxed stability design, which may have contributed to numerous landing accidents that have occurred, including Fedex Express Flight 80 and Lufthansa Cargo Flight 8460.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The Concorde has a well-documented susceptibility to tire failures, experiencing up to 57 failures during its service, in which 32 of the blowouts resulted in damage to the structure, hydraulic systems or engines.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] With the arrival of Wide Area Augmentation System (WAAS), satellite navigation has become accurate enough for altitude as well as positioning use, and is being used increasingly for instrument approaches as well as en-route navigation.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] However, because the GPS constellation is a single point of failure, on-board Inertial Navigation System (INS) or ground-based navigation aids are still required for backup.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In 2017, Rockwell Collins reported it had become more costly to certify than to develop a system, from 75% engineering and 25% certification in past years.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] It calls for a global harmonization between certifying authorities to avoid redundant engineering and certification tests rather than recognizing the others approval and validation.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Parts manufactured without an aviation authority's approval are described as "unapproved".
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Unapproved parts include inferior counterfeits, those used beyond their time limits, those that were previously approved but not properly returned to service, those with fraudulent labels, production overruns that were not sold with the agency's permission, and those that are untraceable.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Unapproved faulty parts have caused hundreds of incidents and crashes, some fatal, including about 24 crashes between 2010 and 2016.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Foreign object debris (FOD) includes items left in the aircraft structure during manufacture/repairs, debris on the runway and solids encountered in flight (e.g. hail and dust).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Such items can damage engines and other parts of the aircraft.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In 2000, Air France Flight 4590 crashed after hitting a part that had fallen from a departing Continental Airlines DC-10.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The crash of Air New Zealand Flight 901 was a result of receiving and interpreting incorrect coordinates, which caused the pilots to inadvertently fly into a mountain.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Boeing studies showed that airliners are struck by lightning twice per year on average; aircraft withstand typical lightning strikes without damage.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The dangers of more powerful positive lightning were not understood until the destruction of a glider in 1999.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] It has since been suggested that positive lightning might have caused the crash of Pan Am Flight 214 in 1963.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] At that time, aircraft were not designed to withstand such strikes because their existence was unknown.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The 1985 standard in force in the US at the time of the glider crash, Advisory Circular AC 20-53A, was replaced by Advisory Circular AC 20-53B in 2006.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] However, it is unclear whether adequate protection against positive lightning was incorporated.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The effects of typical lightning on traditional metal-covered aircraft are well understood and serious damage from a lightning strike on an airplane is rare.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Modern airliners like the Boeing 787 Dreamliner with exteriors and wings made from carbon-fiber-reinforced polymer have been tested and shown to receive no damage from lightning strikes during testing.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Ice and snow can be major factors in airline accidents.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In 2005, Southwest Airlines Flight 1248 slid off the end of a runway after landing in heavy snow conditions, killing one child on the ground.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Even a small amount of icing or coarse frost can greatly impair the ability of a wing to develop adequate lift, which is why regulations prohibit ice, snow or even frost on the wings or tail, prior to takeoff.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Air Florida Flight 90 crashed on takeoff in 1982, as a result of ice/snow on its wings.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] An accumulation of ice during flight can be catastrophic, as evidenced by the loss of control and subsequent crashes of American Eagle Flight 4184 in 1994, and Comair Flight 3272 in 1997.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Both aircraft were turboprop airliners, with straight wings, which tend to be more susceptible to inflight ice accumulation, than are swept-wing jet airliners.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Airlines and airports ensure that aircraft are properly de-iced before takeoff whenever the weather involves icing conditions.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Modern airliners are designed to prevent ice buildup on wings, engines, and tails (empennage) by either routing heated air from jet engines through the leading edges of the wing, and inlets, or on slower aircraft, by use of inflatable rubber "boots" that expand to break off any accumulated ice.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Airline flight plans require airline dispatch offices to monitor the progress of weather along the routes of their flights, helping the pilots to avoid the worst of inflight icing conditions.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Aircraft can also be equipped with an ice detector in order to warn pilots to leave unexpected ice accumulation areas, before the situation becomes critical.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Pitot tubes in modern airplanes and helicopters have been provided with the function of "Pitot Heating" to prevent accidents like Air France Flight 447 caused by the pitot tube freezing and giving false readings.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] A wind shear is a change in wind speed and/or direction over a relatively short distance in the atmosphere.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] A microburst is a localized column of sinking air that drops down in a thunderstorm.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Both of these are potential weather threats that may cause an aviation accident.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Strong outflow from thunderstorms causes rapid changes in the three-dimensional wind velocity just above ground level.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Initially, this outflow causes a headwind that increases airspeed, which normally causes a pilot to reduce engine power if they are unaware of the wind shear.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] As the aircraft passes into the region of the downdraft, the localized headwind diminishes, reducing the aircraft's airspeed and increasing its sink rate.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Then, when the aircraft passes through the other side of the downdraft, the headwind becomes a tailwind, reducing lift generated by the wings, and leaving the aircraft in a low-power, low-speed descent.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] This can lead to an accident if the aircraft is too low to effect a recovery before ground contact.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Between 1964 and 1985, wind shear directly caused or contributed to 26 major civil transport aircraft accidents in the U.S. that led to 620 deaths and 200 injuries.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] An engine may fail to function because of fuel starvation (e.g.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] British Airways Flight 38), fuel exhaustion (e.g.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Air Canada Flight 143), foreign object damage (e.g.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] US Airways Flight 1549), mechanical failure due to metal fatigue (e.g.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Kegworth air disaster, El Al Flight 1862, China Airlines Flight 358), mechanical failure due to improper maintenance (e.g.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] American Airlines Flight 191), mechanical failure caused by an original manufacturing defect in the engine (e.g.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Qantas Flight 32, United Airlines Flight 232, Delta Air Lines Flight 1288), and pilot error (e.g.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In a multi-engine aircraft, failure of a single engine usually results in a precautionary landing being performed, for example, landing at a diversion airport instead of continuing to the intended destination.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] US Airways Flight 1549) or damage to other aircraft systems caused by an uncontained engine failure (e.g.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] United Airlines Flight 232) may, if an emergency landing is not possible, result in the aircraft crashing.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Examples of failure of aircraft structures caused by metal fatigue include the de Havilland Comet accidents (1950s) and Aloha Airlines Flight 243 (1988).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Improper repair procedures can also cause structural failures include Japan Air Lines Flight 123 (1985) and China Airlines Flight 611 (2002).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Now that the subject is better understood, rigorous inspection and nondestructive testing procedures are in place.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Composite materials consist of layers of fibers embedded in a resin matrix.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In some cases, especially when subjected to cyclic stress, the layers of the material separate from each other (delaminate) and lose strength.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] As the failure develops inside the material, nothing is shown on the surface; instrument methods (often ultrasound-based) have to be used to detect such a material failure.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In the 1940s several Yakovlev Yak-9s experienced delamination of plywood in their construction.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] An error in the design of the aircraft itself can be a cause of accidents, even if the error was not the primary cause of the accident.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Examples of this are Lion Air Flight 610 (2018) and Ethiopian Airlines Flight 302 (2019), which both suffered a loss of control in flight leading to both planes crashing.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The cause was discovered to be a design flaw in the Maneuvering Characteristics Augmentation System (MCAS) software that was designed to improve the handling of the Boeing 737 MAX aircraft.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] But instead caused both aircraft to pitch nose down uncontrollably in flight due to a faulty angle of attack sensor, as the design allowed for only one sensor's readings to be used.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Another example is Airlines PNG Flight 1600 (2011) which suffered a fatal forced landing, primarily due to an engine failure.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] This failure was discovered to be caused by a design flaw in the power levers, which allowed the pilot to accidentally place the levers into reverse due to the design of the levers.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Stalling an aircraft (increasing the angle of attack to a point at which the wings fail to produce enough lift) is dangerous and can result in a crash if the pilot fails to make a timely correction.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Devices to warn the pilot when the aircraft's speed is decreasing close to the stall speed include stall warning horns (now standard on virtually all powered aircraft), stick shakers, and voice warnings.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Most stalls are a result of the pilot allowing the airspeed to be too slow for the particular weight and configuration at the time.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Stall speed is higher when ice or frost has attached to the wings and/or tail stabilizer.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The more severe the icing, the higher the stall speed, not only because smooth airflow over the wings becomes increasingly more difficult, but also because of the added weight of the accumulated ice.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Safety regulations control aircraft materials and the requirements for automated fire safety systems.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Usually these requirements take the form of required tests.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The tests measure flammability of materials and toxicity of smoke.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] When the tests fail, it is on a prototype in an engineering laboratory rather than in an aircraft.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Fire and its toxic smoke have been the cause of accidents.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] An electrical fire on Air Canada Flight 797 in 1983 caused the deaths of 23 of the 46 passengers, resulting in the introduction of floor level lighting to assist people to evacuate a smoke-filled aircraft.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In 1985, a fire on the runway caused the loss of 55 lives, 48 from the effects of incapacitating and subsequently lethal toxic gas and smoke in the British Airtours Flight 28M accident which raised serious concerns relating to survivability – something that had not been studied in such detail.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The swift incursion of the fire into the fuselage and the layout of the aircraft impaired passengers' ability to evacuate, with areas such as the forward galley area becoming a bottle-neck for escaping passengers, with some dying very close to the exits.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The use of smoke hoods or misting systems were also examined although both were rejected.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] South African Airways Flight 295 was lost in the Indian Ocean in 1987 after an in-flight fire in the cargo hold could not be suppressed by the crew.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The cargo holds of most airliners are now equipped with automated halon fire extinguishing systems to combat a fire that might occur in the baggage holds.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In May 1996, ValuJet Flight 592 crashed into the Florida Everglades a few minutes after takeoff because of a fire in the forward cargo hold.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] At one time, fire fighting foam paths were laid down before an emergency landing, but the practice was considered only marginally effective, and concerns about the depletion of firefighting capability due to pre-foaming led the United States FAA to withdraw its recommendation in 1987.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] One possible cause of fires in airplanes is wiring problems that involve intermittent faults, such as wires with breached insulation touching each other, having water dripping on them, or short circuits.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Notable was Swissair Flight 111 in 1998 due to an arc in the wiring of IFE which ignited flammable MPET insulation.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] These are difficult to detect once the aircraft is on the ground.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] However, there are methods, such as spread-spectrum time-domain reflectometry, that can feasibly test live wires on aircraft during flight.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Jet engines have to be designed to withstand the ingestion of birds of a specified weight and number and to not lose more than a specified amount of thrust.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The weight and numbers of birds that can be ingested without hazarding the safe flight of the aircraft are related to the engine intake area.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The hazards of ingesting birds beyond the "designed-for" limit were shown on US Airways Flight 1549 when the aircraft struck Canada geese.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The outcome of an ingestion event and whether it causes an accident, be it on a small fast plane, such as military jet fighters, or a large transport, depends on the number and weight of birds and where they strike the fan blade span or the nose cone.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Core damage usually results with impacts near the blade root or on the nose cone.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The highest risk of a bird strike occurs during takeoff and landing in the vicinity of airports, and during low-level flying, for example by military aircraft, crop dusters and helicopters.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Some airports use active countermeasures, including a person with a shotgun, playing recorded sounds of predators through loudspeakers, or employing falconers.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Poisonous grass can be planted that is not palatable to birds, nor to insects that attract insectivorous birds.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Passive countermeasures involve sensible land-use management, avoiding conditions attracting flocks of birds to the area (e.g. landfills).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Another tactic found effective is to let the grass at the airfield grow taller (to approximately 12 inches or 30 centimetres) as some species of birds won't land if they cannot see one another.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Human factors, including pilot error, are another potential set of factors, and currently the factor most commonly found in aviation accidents.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Much progress in applying human factors analysis to improving aviation safety was made around the time of World War II by such pioneers as Paul Fitts and Alphonse Chapanis.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] However, there has been progress in safety throughout the history of aviation, such as the development of the pilot's checklist in 1937.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] CRM, or crew resource management, is a technique that makes use of the experience and knowledge of the complete flight crew to avoid dependence on just one crew member, and to improve pilot decision making.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Pilot error and improper communication are often factors in the collision of aircraft.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] This can take place in the air (1978 Pacific Southwest Airlines Flight 182) (TCAS) or on the ground (1977 Tenerife disaster) (RAAS).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The barriers to effective communication have internal and external factors.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The ability of the flight crew to maintain situational awareness is a critical human factor in air safety.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Human factors training is available to general aviation pilots and called single pilot resource management training.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Failure of the pilots to properly monitor the flight instruments caused the crash of Eastern Air Lines Flight 401 in 1972.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Controlled flight into terrain (CFIT), and error during take-off and landing can have catastrophic consequences, for example causing the crash of Prinair Flight 191 on landing, also in 1972.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Fatigue is particularly prevalent among pilots because of "unpredictable work hours, long duty periods, circadian disruption, and insufficient sleep".
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] These factors can occur together to produce a combination of sleep deprivation, circadian rhythm effects, and 'time-on task' fatigue.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Regulators attempt to mitigate fatigue by limiting the number of hours pilots are allowed to fly over varying periods of time.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Experts in aviation fatigue often find that these methods fall short of their goals.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Rarely, flight crew members are arrested or subject to disciplinary action for being intoxicated on the job.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In 1990, three Northwest Airlines crew members were sentenced to jail for flying while drunk.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In 2001, Northwest fired a pilot who failed a breathalyzer test after a flight.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In July 2002, both pilots of America West Airlines Flight 556 were arrested just before they were scheduled to fly because they had been drinking alcohol.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The pilots were fired and the FAA revoked their pilot licenses.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] At least one fatal airliner accident involving drunk pilots occurred when Aero Flight 311 crashed at Kvevlax, Finland, killing all 25 on board in 1961.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Another example is the crash Aeroflot Flight 821, in which the captain's intoxication contributed to the accident, killing all 88 on board.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] There have been rare instances of suicide by pilots.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Although most air crew are screened for psychological fitness, a very few authorized pilots have flown acts of suicide and even mass murder.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In 1982, Japan Airlines Flight 350 crashed while on approach to the Tokyo Haneda Airport, killing 24 of the 174 on board.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The official investigation found the mentally ill captain had attempted suicide by placing the inboard engines into reverse thrust, while the aircraft was close to the runway.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The first officer did not have enough time to countermand before the aircraft stalled and crashed.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In 1997, SilkAir Flight 185 suddenly went into a high dive from its cruising altitude.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The speed of the dive was so high that the aircraft began to break apart before it finally crashed near Palembang, Sumatra.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] After three years of investigation, the Indonesian authorities declared that the cause of the accident could not be determined.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] However, the US NTSB concluded that deliberate suicide by the captain was the only reasonable explanation.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In 1999 in the case of EgyptAir Flight 990, it appears that the first officer deliberately crashed into the Atlantic Ocean while the captain was away from his station.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Crew involvement is one of the speculative theories in the disappearance of Malaysia Airlines Flight 370 on 8 March 2014.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] All 144 passengers and six crew members were killed.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The crash was intentionally caused by the co-pilot, Andreas Lubitz.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Having been declared 'unfit to work' without telling his employer, Lubitz reported for duty, and during the flight locked the captain out of the flight-deck.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In response to the incident and the circumstances of Lubitz's involvement, aviation authorities in Canada, New Zealand, Germany, and Australia implemented new regulations that require two authorised personnel to be present in the cockpit at all times.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Three days after the incident, the European Aviation Safety Agency (EASA) issued a temporary recommendation for airlines to ensure that at least two crew members, including at least one pilot, are in the cockpit at all times of the flight.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Several airlines announced they had already adopted similar policies voluntarily.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Inaction, omission, failure to act as required, willful disregard of safety procedures, disdain for rules, and unjustifiable risk-taking by pilots have also led to accidents and incidents.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Although Smartwings QS-1125 flight of 22 August 2019 successfully made an emergency landing at destination, the captain was censured for failing to follow mandatory procedures, including for not landing at the nearest possible diversion airport after an engine failure.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Unsafe human factors are not limited to pilot errors.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Third party factors include ground crew mishaps, ground vehicle to aircraft collisions and engineering maintenance related problems.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] For example, failure to properly close a cargo door on Turkish Airlines Flight 981 in 1974 caused the loss of the aircraft.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Another anti-CFIT tool is the Minimum Safe Altitude Warning (MSAW) system which monitors the altitudes transmitted by aircraft transponders and compares that with the system's defined minimum safe altitudes for a given area.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] When the system determines the aircraft is lower, or might soon be lower, than the minimum safe altitude, the air traffic controller receives an acoustic and visual warning and then alerts the pilot that the aircraft is too low.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The use of certain electronic equipment is partially or entirely prohibited as it might interfere with aircraft operation, such as causing compass deviations.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Use of some types of personal electronic devices is prohibited when an aircraft is below 10,000 feet (3,000 m), taking off, or landing.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Use of a mobile phone is prohibited on most flights because in-flight usage creates problems with ground-based cells.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Wireless devices such as cellphones feature an airplane mode.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Various ground support equipment operate in close proximity to the fuselage and wings to service the aircraft and occasionally cause accidental damage in the form of scratches in the paint or small dents in the skin.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] However, because aircraft structures (including the outer skin) play such a critical role in the safe operation of a flight, all damage is inspected, measured, and possibly tested to ensure that any damage is within safe tolerances.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] An example problem was the depressurization incident on Alaska Airlines Flight 536 in 2005.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] During ground services, a baggage handler hit the side of the aircraft with a tug towing a train of baggage carts.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] This damaged the metal skin of the aircraft.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] This damage was not reported and the plane departed.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Climbing through 26,000 feet (7,900 m) the damaged section of the skin gave way under the difference in pressure between the inside of the aircraft and the outside air.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The cabin depressurized explosively necessitating a rapid descent to denser (breathable) air and an emergency landing.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Post-landing examination of the fuselage revealed a 12-inch (30 cm) hole on the right side of the airplane.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Plumes of volcanic ash near active volcanoes can damage propellers, engines and cockpit windows.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In 1982, British Airways Flight 9 flew through an ash cloud and temporarily lost power from all four engines.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The plane was badly damaged, with all the leading edges being scratched.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The front windscreens had been so badly "sand" blasted by the ash that they could not be used to land the aircraft.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Prior to 2010 the general approach taken by airspace regulators was that if the ash concentration rose above zero, then the airspace was considered unsafe and was consequently closed.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Volcanic Ash Advisory Centers enable liaison between meteorologists, volcanologists, and the aviation industry.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The last two types can be prevented with airport surveillance and broadcast systems, a Runway Awareness and Advisory System, and landing navigation systems (e.g. transponder landing system, microwave landing system, instrument landing system).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Aircrew are normally trained to handle hijack situations.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Since the September 11, 2001 attacks, stricter airport and airline security measures are in place to prevent terrorism, such as security checkpoints and locking the cockpit doors during flight.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In the United States, the Federal Flight Deck Officer program is run by the Federal Air Marshal Service, with the aim of training active and licensed airline pilots to carry weapons and defend their aircraft against criminal activity and terrorism.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Upon completion of government training, selected pilots enter a covert law enforcement and counter-terrorism service.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Their jurisdiction is normally limited to a flight deck or a cabin of a commercial airliner or a cargo aircraft they operate while on duty.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Passenger planes have rarely been attacked in both peacetime and war.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Earlier tragedies investigations and improved engineering has allowed many safety improvements that have allowed an increasing safer aviation.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Airport design and location can have a large impact on aviation safety, especially since some airports such as Chicago Midway International Airport were originally built for propeller planes and many airports are in congested areas where it is difficult to meet newer safety standards.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] For instance, the FAA issued rules in 1999 calling for a runway safety area, usually extending 150 metres (500 ft) to each side and 300 metres (1,000 ft) beyond the end of a runway.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] This is intended to cover ninety percent of the cases of an aircraft leaving the runway by providing a buffer space free of obstacles.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Many older airports do not meet this standard.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] One method of substituting for the 300 metres (1,000 ft) at the end of a runway for airports in congested areas is to install an engineered materials arrestor system (EMAS).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] These systems are usually made of lightweight, crushable concrete that absorbs the energy of the aircraft to bring it to a rapid stop.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] As of 2008, they have stopped three aircraft at JFK Airport.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] According to a 2000 report by the National Transportation Safety Board, emergency aircraft evacuations happen about once every 11 days in the U.S.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] While some situations are extremely dire, such as when the plane is on fire, in many cases the greatest challenge for passengers can be the use of the evacuation slide.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In a *Time* article on the subject, Amanda Ripley reported that when a new supersized Airbus A380 underwent mandatory evacuation tests in 2006, thirty-three of the 873 evacuating volunteers got hurt.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] While the evacuation was considered a success, one volunteer suffered a broken leg, while the remaining 32 received slide burns.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] In her article, Ripley provided tips on how to make it down the airplane slide without injury.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Another improvement to airplane evacuations is the requirement by the Federal Aviation Administration for planes to demonstrate an evacuation time of 90 seconds with half the emergency exits blocked for each type of airplane in their fleet.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] According to studies, 90 seconds is the time needed to evacuate before the plane starts burning, before there can be a very large fire or explosions, or before fumes fill the cabin.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Changes such as using new materials for seat fabric and insulation has given between 40 and 60 additional seconds to people on board to evacuate before the cabin gets filled with fire and potential deadly fumes.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Other improvements through the years include the use of properly rated seatbelts, impact resistant seat frames, and airplane wings and engines designed to shear off to absorb impact forces.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] As the result of the accidents due to wind shear and other weather disturbances, most notably the 1985 crash of Delta Air Lines Flight 191, the U.S.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Federal Aviation Administration mandated that all commercial aircraft have on-board wind shear detection systems by 1993.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] Since 1995, the number of major civil aircraft accidents caused by wind shear has dropped to approximately one every ten years, due to the mandated on-board detection as well as the addition of Doppler weather radar units on the ground (NEXRAD).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p01] The installation of high-resolution Terminal Doppler Weather Radar stations at many U.S. airports that are commonly affected by wind shear has further aided the ability of pilots and ground controllers to avoid wind shear conditions.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p02] Air safety investigators are trained and authorized to investigate aviation accidents and incidents: to research, analyse, and report their conclusions.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p02] They may be specialized in flight operations, training, aircraft structures, air traffic control, flight recorders or human factors.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p02] They are employed by government organizations responsible for aviation safety, manufacturers or unions, though only government organizations have statutory powers to investigate.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p02] The safety improvement initiatives are aviation safety partnerships between regulators, manufacturers, operators, professional unions, research organizations, and international aviation organizations to further enhance safety.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p02] Since pilot error accounts for between one-third and 60% of aviation accidents, advances in automation and technology could replace some or all of the duties of the aircraft pilots.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p02] Automation since the 1980s has already eliminated the need for flight engineers.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p02] In complex situations with severely degraded systems, the problem-solving and judgment capability of humans is challenging to achieve with automated systems, for example the catastrophic engine failures experienced by United Airlines Flight 232 and Qantas Flight 32.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p02] However, with more accurate software modeling of aeronautic factors, test planes have been successfully flown in these conditions.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p02] While the accident rate is very low, to ensure they do not rise with the air transport growth, experts recommend creating a robust culture of collecting information from employees without blame.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p02] Advancements in satellite navigation, digital flight data, and instrument flight procedure design have significantly contributed to reducing controlled flight into terrain (CFIT) incidents.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/air-safety-p02] Implementation of WAAS/LPV and RNP approaches provides improved vertical guidance, while PBN-based helicopter procedures enhance safety during low-visibility and low-altitude operations.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] An **airbreathing jet engine** (or **ducted jet engine**) is a jet engine in which the exhaust gas which supplies jet propulsion is atmospheric air, which is taken in, compressed, heated, and expanded back to atmospheric pressure through a propelling nozzle.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Compression may be provided by a gas turbine, as in the original turbojet and newer turbofan, or arise solely from the ram pressure of the vehicle's velocity, as with the ramjet and pulsejet.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] All practical airbreathing jet engines heat the air by burning fuel.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Alternatively a heat exchanger may be used, as in a nuclear-powered jet engine.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Most modern jet engines are turbofans, which are more fuel efficient than turbojets because the thrust supplied by the gas turbine is augmented by bypass air passing through a ducted fan.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The original air-breathing gas turbine jet engine was the turbojet.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] It was a concept brought to life by two engineers, Frank Whittle in England UK and Hans von Ohain in Germany.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The turbojet compresses and heats air and then exhausts it as a high speed, high temperature jet to create thrust.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] While these engines are capable of giving high thrust levels, they are most efficient at very high speeds (over Mach 1), due to the low-mass-flow, high speed nature of the jet exhaust.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Modern turbofans are a development of the turbojet; they are basically turbojets that include a new section called the *fan stage*.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Rather than using all their exhaust gases to provide direct thrust like a turbojet, turbofan engines extract some of the power from the exhaust gases inside the engine and use it to power the fan stage.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The fan stage accelerates a large volume of air through a duct, bypassing the *engine core* (the actual gas turbine component of the engine), and expelling it at the rear as a jet, creating thrust.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] A proportion of the air that comes through the fan stage enters the engine core rather than being ducted to the rear, and is thus compressed and heated; some of the energy is extracted to power the compressors and fans, while the remainder is exhausted at the rear.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] This high-speed, hot-gas exhaust blends with the low speed, cool-air exhaust from the fan stage, and both contribute to the overall thrust of the engine.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Depending on what proportion of cool air is bypassed around the engine core, a turbofan can be called *low-bypass*, *high-bypass*, or *very-high-bypass* engines.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Over the last several decades, there has been a move towards *very high bypass* engines, which use fans far larger than the engine core itself, which is typically a modern, high efficiency two or three-spool design.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Airbreathing jet engines are nearly always internal combustion engines that obtain propulsion from the combustion of fuel inside the engine.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Oxygen present in the atmosphere is used to oxidise a fuel source, typically a hydrocarbon-based jet fuel.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The burning mixture expands greatly in volume, driving heated air through a propelling nozzle.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Two engineers, Frank Whittle in the UK and Hans von Ohain in Germany, developed the **turbojet** concept independently into practical engines during the late 1930s.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turbojets consist of an inlet, a compressor, a combustor, a turbine (that drives the compressor) and a propelling nozzle.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turbojets have a low propulsive efficiency below about Mach 2 and produce a lot of jet noise, both a result of the very high velocity of the exhaust.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Modern jet propelled aircraft are powered by turbofans.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] These engines, with their lower exhaust velocities, produce less jet noise and use less fuel.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turbojets are still used to power medium range cruise missiles due to their high exhaust speed, low frontal area, which reduces drag, and relative simplicity, which reduces cost.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The low pressure compressor (LPC), usually known as a fan, compresses air into a bypass duct whilst its inner portion supercharges the core compressor.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The fan is often an integral part of a multi-stage core LPC.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The bypass airflow either passes to a separate 'cold nozzle' or mixes with low pressure turbine exhaust gases, before expanding through a 'mixed flow nozzle'.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In the 1960s there was little difference between civil and military jet engines, apart from the use of afterburning in some (supersonic) applications.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Today, turbofans are used for airliners because they have an exhaust speed that is better matched to the subsonic flight speed of the airliner.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] At airliner flight speeds, the exhaust speed from a turbojet engine is excessively high and wastes energy.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The lower exhaust speed from a turbofan gives better fuel consumption.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The increased airflow from the fan gives higher thrust at low speeds.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The lower exhaust speed also gives much lower jet noise.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The comparatively large frontal fan has several effects.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Compared to a turbojet of identical thrust, a turbofan has a much larger air mass flow rate and the flow through the bypass duct generates a significant fraction of the thrust.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The additional duct air has not been ignited, which gives it a slow speed, but no extra fuel is needed to provide this thrust.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Instead, the energy is taken from the central core, which gives it also a reduced exhaust speed.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The average velocity of the mixed exhaust air is thus reduced (low specific thrust) which is less wasteful of energy but reduces the top speed.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Overall, a turbofan can be much more fuel efficient and quieter, and it turns out that the fan also allows greater net thrust to be available at slow speeds.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Thus civil turbofans today have a low exhaust speed (low *specific thrust* – net thrust divided by airflow) to keep jet noise to a minimum and to improve fuel efficiency.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Consequently, the bypass ratio (bypass flow divided by core flow) is relatively high (ratios from 4:1 up to 8:1 are common), with the Rolls-Royce Trent XWB approaching 10:1.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Only a single fan stage is required, because a low specific thrust implies a low fan pressure ratio.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turbofans designed for subsonic civilian aircraft also usually have a just a single front fan, because their additional thrust is generated by a large additional mass of air which is only moderately compressed, rather than a smaller amount of air which is greatly compressed.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Military turbofans, however, have a relatively high specific thrust, to maximize the thrust for a given frontal area, jet noise being of less concern in military uses relative to civil uses.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Multistage fans are normally needed to reach the relatively high fan pressure ratio needed for high specific thrust.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Although high turbine inlet temperatures are often employed, the bypass ratio tends to be low, usually significantly less than 2.0.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turboprop engines are jet engine derivatives, still gas turbines, that extract work from the hot-exhaust jet to turn a rotating shaft, which is then used to produce thrust by some other means.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] While not strictly jet engines in that they rely on an auxiliary mechanism to produce thrust, turboprops are very similar to other turbine-based jet engines, and are often described as such.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In turboprop engines, a portion of the engine's thrust is produced by spinning a propeller, rather than relying solely on high-speed jet exhaust.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Producing thrust both ways, turboprops are occasionally referred to as a type of hybrid jet engine.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] They differ from turbofans in that a traditional propeller, rather than a ducted fan, provides the majority of thrust.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Most turboprops use gear-reduction between the turbine and the propeller.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] (Geared turbofans also feature gear reduction, but they are less common.) The hot-jet exhaust is an important minority of thrust, and maximum thrust is obtained by matching the two thrust contributions.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turboprops generally have better performance than turbojets or turbofans at low speeds where propeller efficiency is high, but become increasingly noisy and inefficient at high speeds.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turboshaft engines are very similar to turboprops, differing in that nearly all energy in the exhaust is extracted to spin the rotating shaft, which is used to power machinery rather than a propeller, they therefore generate little to no jet thrust and are often used to power helicopters.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] A propfan engine (also called a "propjet", "unducted fan", "open rotor", or "ultra-high bypass") is a jet engine that uses its gas generator to power an exposed fan, similar to turboprop engines.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Like turboprop engines, propfans generate most of their thrust from the propeller and not the exhaust jet.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The primary difference between turboprop and propfan design is that the propeller blades on a propfan are highly swept to allow them to operate at speeds around Mach 0.8, which is competitive with modern commercial turbofans.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] These engines have the fuel efficiency advantages of turboprops with the performance capability of commercial turbofans.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] While significant research and testing (including flight testing) has been conducted on propfans, none have entered production.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The various components named above have constraints on how they are put together to generate the most efficiency or performance.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The performance and efficiency of an engine can never be taken in isolation; for example fuel/distance efficiency of a supersonic jet engine maximises at about Mach 2, whereas the drag for the vehicle carrying it is increasing as a square law and has much extra drag in the transonic region.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The highest fuel efficiency for the overall vehicle is thus typically around Mach 0.85.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The thermodynamics of a typical air-breathing jet engine are modeled approximately by a **Brayton Cycle** which is a thermodynamic cycle that describes the workings of the gas turbine engine, which is the basis of the airbreathing jet engine and others.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] It is named after George Brayton (1830–1892), the American engineer who developed it, although it was originally proposed and patented by Englishman John Barber in 1791.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] It is also sometimes known as the **Joule cycle**.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The nominal net thrust quoted for a jet engine usually refers to the Sea Level Static (SLS) condition, either for the International Standard Atmosphere (ISA) or a hot day condition (e.g.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] As an example, the GE90-76B has a take-off static thrust of 76,000 lbf (360 kN) at SLS, ISA+15 °C.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Naturally, net thrust will decrease with altitude, because of the lower air density.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] There is also, however, a flight speed effect.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Initially as the aircraft gains speed down the runway, there will be little increase in nozzle pressure and temperature, because the ram rise in the intake is very small.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] There will also be little change in mass flow.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Consequently, nozzle gross thrust initially only increases marginally with flight speed.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] However, being an air breathing engine (unlike a conventional rocket) there is a penalty for taking on-board air from the atmosphere.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Although the penalty is zero at static conditions, it rapidly increases with flight speed, causing the net thrust to be eroded.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] As flight speed builds up after take-off, the ram rise in the intake starts to have a significant effect upon nozzle pressure/temperature and intake airflow, causing nozzle gross thrust to climb more rapidly.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] This term now starts to offset the still increasing ram drag, eventually causing net thrust to start to increase.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In some engines, the net thrust at say Mach 1.0, sea level can even be slightly greater than the static thrust.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Above Mach 1.0, with a subsonic inlet design, shock losses tend to decrease net thrust, however a suitably designed supersonic inlet can give a lower reduction in intake pressure recovery, allowing net thrust to continue to climb in the supersonic regime.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Jet engines are usually very reliable and have a very good safety record.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In some cases in jet engines the conditions in the engine due to airflow entering the engine or other variations can cause the compressor blades to stall.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] When this occurs the pressure in the engine blows out past the blades, and the stall is maintained until the pressure has decreased, and the engine has lost all thrust.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The compressor blades will then usually come out of stall, and re-pressurize the engine.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] If conditions are not corrected, the cycle will usually repeat.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Depending on the engine this can be highly damaging to the engine and creates worrying vibrations for the crew.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Fan, compressor or turbine blade failures have to be contained within the engine casing.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] To do this the engine has to be designed to pass blade containment tests as specified by certification authorities.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Bird ingestion is the term used when birds enter the intake of a jet engine.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] It is a common aircraft safety hazard and has caused fatal accidents.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In 1988 an Ethiopian Airlines Boeing 737 ingested pigeons into both engines during take-off and then crashed in an attempt to return to the Bahir Dar airport; of the 104 people aboard, 35 died and 21 were injured.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In another incident in 1995, a Dassault Falcon 20 crashed at a Paris airport during an emergency landing attempt after ingesting lapwings into an engine, which caused an engine failure and a fire in the airplane fuselage; all 10 people on board were killed.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Jet engines have to be designed to withstand the ingestion of birds of a specified weight and number, and to not lose more than a specified amount of thrust.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In 2009, an Airbus A320 aircraft, US Airways Flight 1549, ingested one Canada goose into each engine.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The plane ditched in the Hudson River after taking off from LaGuardia International Airport in New York City.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The incident illustrated the hazards of ingesting birds beyond the "designed-for" limit.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Few birds fly high, so the greatest risk of a bird ingestion is during takeoff and landing and during low level flying.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] If a jet plane is flying through air contaminated with volcanic ash, there is risk that ingested ash will cause erosion damage to the compressor blades, blockage of fuel nozzle air holes and blockage of the turbine cooling passages.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Some of these effects may cause the engine to surge or flame-out during the flight.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Re-lights are usually successful after flame-outs but with considerable loss of altitude.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] It was the case of British Airways Flight 9 which flew through volcanic dust at 37,000 ft.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] All 4 engines flamed out and re-light attempts were successful at about 13,000 ft.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] One class of failure that has caused accidents is the uncontained failure, where rotating parts of the engine break off and exit through the case.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] These high energy parts can cut fuel and control lines, and can penetrate the cabin.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Although fuel and control lines are usually duplicated for reliability, the crash of United Airlines Flight 232 was caused when hydraulic fluid lines for all three independent hydraulic systems were simultaneously severed by shrapnel from an uncontained engine failure.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Prior to the United 232 crash, the probability of a simultaneous failure of all three hydraulic systems was considered as high as a billion-to-one.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] However, the statistical models used to come up with this figure did not account for the fact that the number-two engine was mounted at the tail close to all the hydraulic lines, nor the possibility that an engine failure would release fragments in multiple directions.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Since then, more modern aircraft engine designs have focused on keeping shrapnel from penetrating the cowling or ductwork, and have increasingly utilized high-strength composite materials to achieve the required penetration resistance while keeping the weight low.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In 2007 the cost of jet fuel, while highly variable from one airline to another, averaged 26.5% of total operating costs, making it the single largest operating expense for most airlines.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Jet engines are usually run on fossil fuels and are thus a source of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Jet engines can also run on biofuels or hydrogen, although hydrogen is usually produced from fossil fuels.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] About 7.2% of the oil used in 2004 was consumed by jet engines.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Some scientists believe that jet engines are also a source of global dimming due to the water vapour in the exhaust causing cloud formations.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Nitrogen compounds are also formed during the combustion process from reactions with atmospheric nitrogen.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] At low altitudes this is not thought to be especially harmful, but for supersonic aircraft that fly in the stratosphere some destruction of ozone may occur.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Sulphates are also emitted if the fuel contains sulphur.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] A ramjet is a form of airbreathing jet engine using the engine's forward motion to compress incoming air, without a rotary compressor.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Ramjets cannot produce thrust at zero airspeed and thus cannot move an aircraft from a standstill.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Ramjets require considerable forward speed to operate well, and as a class work most efficiently at speeds around Mach 3.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] This type of jet can operate up to speeds of Mach 6.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] They consist of three sections; an inlet to compress incoming air, a combustor to inject and combust fuel, and a nozzle to expel the hot gases and produce thrust.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Ramjets require a relatively high speed to efficiently compress the incoming air, so ramjets cannot operate at a standstill and they are most efficient at supersonic speeds.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] A key trait of ramjet engines is that combustion is done at subsonic speeds.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The supersonic incoming air is dramatically slowed through the inlet, where it is then combusted at the much slower, subsonic, speeds.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The faster the incoming air is, however, the less efficient it becomes to slow it to subsonic speeds.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Therefore, ramjet engines are limited to approximately Mach 5.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] They have also been used successfully, though not efficiently, as tip jets on helicopter rotors.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Pulsejets are subsonic engines which also use ram compression, but with intermittent combustion unlike the continuous combustion used in a ramjet.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] They are a quite distinct type of jet engine.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Scramjets are an evolution of ramjets that are able to operate at much higher speeds than any other kind of airbreathing engine.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] They share a similar structure with ramjets, being a specially shaped tube that compresses air with no moving parts through ram-air compression.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] They consist of an inlet, a combustor, and a nozzle.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The primary difference between ramjets and scramjets is that scramjets do not slow the oncoming airflow to subsonic speeds for combustion.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Thus, scramjets do not have the diffuser required by ramjets to slow the incoming airflow to subsonic speeds.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Scramjets start working at speeds of at least Mach 4, and have a maximum useful speed of approximately Mach 17.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Due to aerodynamic heating at these high speeds, cooling poses a challenge to engineers.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Since scramjets use supersonic combustion they can operate at speeds above Mach 6 where traditional ramjets are too inefficient.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Very few scramjet engines have ever been built and flown.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In May 2010 the Boeing X-51 set the endurance record for the longest scramjet burn at over 200 seconds.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turbojet operation over the complete flight envelope from zero to Mach 3+ requires features to allow the compressor to function properly at the high inlet temperatures beyond Mach 2.5 as well as at low flight speeds.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The J58 compressor solution was to bleed airflow from the 4th compressor stage at speeds above about Mach 2.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The bleed flow, 20% at Mach 3, was returned to the engine via 6 external tubes to cool the afterburner liner and primary nozzle as well as to provide extra air for combustion.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The J58 engine was the only operational turbojet engine, being designed to operate continuously even at maximum afterburning, for Mach 3.2 cruise.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] An alternative solution is seen in a contemporary installation, which did not reach operational status, the Mach 3 GE YJ93/XB-70.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Yet another solution was specified in a proposal for a Mach 3 reconnaissance Phantom.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] This was pre-compressor cooling, albeit available for relatively short duration.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Jet engines can be run on almost any fuel.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Hydrogen is a highly desirable fuel, as, although the energy per mole is not unusually high, the molecule is very much lighter than other molecules.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The energy per kg of hydrogen is twice that of more common fuels and this gives twice the specific impulse.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In addition, jet engines running on hydrogen are quite easy to build—the first ever turbojet was run on hydrogen.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Also, although not duct engines, hydrogen-fueled rocket engines have seen extensive use.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] However, in almost every other way, hydrogen is problematic.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The downside of hydrogen is its density; in gaseous form the tanks are impractical for flight, but even in the form of liquid hydrogen it has a density one fourteenth that of water.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] It is also deeply cryogenic and requires very significant insulation that precludes it being stored in wings.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The overall vehicle would end up being very large, and difficult for most airports to accommodate.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Finally, pure hydrogen is not found in nature, and must be manufactured either via steam reforming or expensive electrolysis.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] A few experimental hydrogen-powered aircraft have flown with propellers, and jets have been proposed that may be feasible.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Carmichael in 1955 is that hydrogen-fueled engines could theoretically have much higher performance than hydrocarbon-fueled engines if a heat exchanger were used to cool the incoming air.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The low temperature allows lighter materials to be used, a higher mass-flow through the engines, and permits combustors to inject more fuel without overheating the engine.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] This idea leads to plausible designs like Reaction Engines SABRE, that might permit single-stage-to-orbit launch vehicles, and ATREX, which could permit jet engines to be used up to hypersonic speeds and high altitudes for boosters for launch vehicles.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The idea is also being researched by the EU for a concept to achieve non-stop antipodal supersonic passenger travel at Mach 5 (Reaction Engines A2).
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The **air turborocket** is a form of combined-cycle jet engine.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The basic layout includes a gas generator, which produces high pressure gas, that drives a turbine/compressor assembly which compresses atmospheric air into a combustion chamber.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] This mixture is then combusted before leaving the device through a nozzle and creating thrust.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] There are different types of air turborockets.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The various types generally differ in how the gas generator section of the engine functions.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Air turborockets are often referred to as **turboramjets**, **turboramjet rockets**, **turborocket expanders**, and others.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] As there is no consensus on which names apply to which specific concepts, various sources may use the same name for two different concepts.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In multiple cases, instead of expressing rotor speeds (N1, N2) as RPM on cockpit displays, pilots are provided with the speeds expressed as a percentage of the design point speed.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] For example, at full power, the N1 might be 101.5% or 100%.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] This user interface decision has been made as a human factors consideration, since pilots are more likely to notice a problem with a two- or 3-digit percentage (where 100% implies a nominal value) than with a 5-digit RPM.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/atrex] The **ATREX** engine (**Air Turbo Ramjet Engine with eXpander cycle**) developed in Japan is an experimental precooled jet engine that works as a turbojet at low speeds and a ramjet up to mach 6.0.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/atrex] ATREX uses liquid hydrogen fuel in a fairly exotic single-fan arrangement.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/atrex] The liquid hydrogen fuel is pumped through a heat exchanger in the air-intake, simultaneously heating the liquid hydrogen and cooling the incoming air.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/atrex] This cooling of the incoming air is critical in achieving a reasonable efficiency.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/atrex] The hydrogen then continues through a second heat exchanger positioned after the combustion section, where the hot exhaust is used to further heat the hydrogen, turning it in a very high pressure gas.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/atrex] This gas is then passed through the tips of the fan providing driving power to the fan at subsonic speeds.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/atrex] After mixing with the air, the hydrogen is burned in the combustion chamber.
[src:airbreathing-jet-engine/atrex] The development of this engine lost focus in favor of the new hypersonic precooled turbojet engine (PCTJ).
